You want `f` to also depend on a parameter which plays no role. See `nat_strong_rec` which has a type `α` which is just passed to every function. (This is used in larger constructions to contain all the variables that are fixed in the recursion.)
Proved the lemma.
This could be strengthened to `List.infix`
add `infix_bind_of_mem`

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion have : m a₁ ≤ m a - k := Nat.lt_succ.mp (by simpa [← Nat.succ_sub this] using ih a₁ ha₁) ```
This looks like it should be factored through `filterMap`: `bs.bind (fun i => (f i).toList) = bs.filterMap f`, and then the congruence of `filterMap` and equality to `map` should already exist

```suggestion
private def bindList (l : β → List β) (b : β) : ℕ → List β := fun n =>
  n.rec [b] (fun _ bs => bs.bind l)
```
Can all of these `private def` and `private lemma` be moved into `nat_omega_rec'` as `let` and `have` respectively?

Following the [naming convention](https://leanprover-community.github.io/contribute/naming.html), namespaces should be appended in came case when the unnamespaced name is ambiguous.
```suggestion
theorem optionToList : Primrec (Option.toList : Option α → List α) :=
```

```suggestion
theorem listFilterMap {f : α → List β} {g : α → β → Option σ}
```
or just
```suggestion
theorem filterMap {f : α → List β} {g : α → β → Option σ}
```
because I think `filterMap` unambiguously means `List.filterMap`

```suggestion
theorem filterMap_eq_map_of_forall_eq_some {f : α → Option β} {g : α → β} {l : List α}
```
Is this lemma true as an iff, btw? If so, can you write that iff (and remove the current, weaker, lemma)?
ok. I proved the iff, and named it `filterMap_eq_map_iff_forall_eq_some`.

```suggestion
theorem listLookup [DecidableEq α] : Primrec₂ (List.lookup : α → List (α × β) → Option β) :=
```
or
```suggestion
theorem lookup [DecidableEq α] : Primrec₂ (List.lookup : α → List (α × β) → Option β) :=
```

This is probably more readable:
```suggestion
    l.filterMap f = l.map g ↔ ∀ x ∈ l, f x = some (g x) where
  mp := by induction' l with a l ih
    · simp
    cases' ha : f a with b <;> simp [ha]
    · intro h
      simpa [show (filterMap f l).length = l.length + 1 from by simp[h], Nat.add_one_le_iff]
        using List.length_filterMap_le f l
    · rintro rfl h
      exact ⟨rfl, ih h⟩,
  mpr h := Eq.trans (filterMap_congr $ by simpa) (congr_fun (List.filterMap_eq_map _) _)
```
